column1: #Text=Depoe Bay is a town on the Central Oregon Coast , famous as the smallest navigable harbor in the world , and as the " whale watching capital of the world . "
#Text=Lots of research going on , mostly connected to Oregon State University 's oceanography department .
#Text=Depoe Bay is relatively easy to get to .
#Text=If you are coming from the south on Hwy 101 , continue past Newport for 27 miles .
#Text=For travellers starting in Corvallis , for instance , head west on Hwy 34 and continue to Newport ; turn north onto Hwy 101 , again for 27 miles .
#Text=Hwy 101 is renowned as the major Oregon/California coast highway .
#Text=Drive ( slowly ) if you must , but the best way to see everything is to walk .
#Text=There 's a pedestrian underpass to cross Hwy 101 at the bridge- this can be easier than trying to cross 101 between shops and the seawall /Whale Watching center on busy weekends .
#Text=Whale watching is a very popular thing these days with about 95 percent of Oregonians/world travellers watching whales from this town .
#Text=Depoe Bay really is preferred by the grey whales for showing themselves ( and showing off ) more than anywhere else .
#Text=For extraordinary views of the Pacific Ocean in general , there are several other lookout points in town as well .
#Text=Many miles of accessible beach at Depoe Bay ; check the weather for suitable activities .
#Text=Boiler Bay State Scenic Viewpoint ( Hwy.101 , 1 mile North of Depoe Bay ) , ☏ +541-265-4560 .
#Text=See the rugged bay from the parking/ picnic area on the rocky cliffs .
#Text=The bay is named for a 1910 shipwreck , and the ships boiler can be seen at extreme low tide .
#Text=This is a good place to watch for resident grey whales year round , as well as ocean-going birds .
#Text=A cliff-rimmed beach where a creek flows into the ocean .
#Text=Good place to tide pool or bird watch .
#Text=There`s also both wind-sheltered and covered picnic structures .
#Text=Inland , wooden footbridges lead you through the Sitka spruce , western hemlock , shore pine and alder forest .
#Text=Justin Sparks Wildlife Art ( The Sparks Gallery ) , 46 N US 101 , ☏ +1 541-891-3335 .
#Text=Before becoming an artist , Justin Sparks worked with animals at zoos and sanctuaries .
#Text=Head to the beach , after checking the wave/weather situation .
#Text=The Chamber of Commerce has the latest information on whom to contact , businesses , phone numbers , etc.
#Text=Watch the waves crash into the rocks from lookout points , most on Hwy 101 .

#Text=Retailers offer country decor , surfing items , coffee drinks , restaurant/cafe specialities , etc. ; other small private venues showcase the local craftspersons , with many unique items available .
